kname from Old French  <i>mal leverier</i> ‘bad harrier’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":85,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Mauleverer was born in 1230, in Woodsetts, Yorkshire, England, his father, Henry Mauleverer, was 25 and his mother